WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.660
I call AZD0120 the sniper CAR-T.

00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:09.720
This is one of the CAR-Ts that I honestly was so scared of when we first started the

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:11.520
trials because I didn't know what was going to happen.

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:13.580
They're manufacturing so fast.

00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:17.520
They actually encourage not doing bridging if patients aren't just rip-roaring disease.

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:21.200
And it really scared me because, again, every time I get up here, I talk about how much

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:22.520
bridging is important for toxicity.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:26.780
And at least for me, the patients that have been on have done so well, and they haven't

00:00:26.780 --> 00:00:27.740
had any side effects.

00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:29.420
And I thought they didn't respond then.

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:30.600
I was like, OK, it didn't work.

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:34.440
And then all of a sudden, they're in CRs and a year or longer out and doing amazingly.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:38.460
So again, I call it the sniper CAR-T, which I think is pretty fantastic.

00:00:39.180 --> 00:00:42.020
So again, we know that there's unmet needs.

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:43.440
And how can we improve CAR-T?

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:49.240
I guess the big question for me and what I'm going to hear from my panel and even Dr.

00:00:49.300 --> 00:00:54.960
Garfall, who's actually done some of the CD19 BCMA work way, way back in the day, the

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:58.000
original one, is CD19 really what we're going after?

00:00:58.060 --> 00:00:58.800
I don't know, right?

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:03.940
I know there's some cells that look like they are pre-myeloma cells, stem cells.

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:09.660
But what I really think makes this CAR different is the way it's manufactured and actually

00:01:09.660 --> 00:01:13.260
the type of CAR-Ts that we're getting into our patients.

00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:17.880
Again, with CAR-T cell therapy in general, when I get a product, I actually don't know

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:19.640
what I'm giving my patient that day, right?

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:21.080
That's the biggest unknown.

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:22.780
And so it matters.

00:01:22.920 --> 00:01:24.060
I really do think it matters.

00:01:24.220 --> 00:01:28.820
And maybe, again, because these are not going to be in culture for very long, I don't know

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:31.160
how long, and they are more T-cell, central memory cells.

00:01:31.540 --> 00:01:33.240
Maybe that's why they act the way they do.

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:34.540
So, okay.

00:01:34.740 --> 00:01:38.980
So, again, manufacturing, they do see more T-stem cell memory cells.

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:40.940
They're less exhausted phenotype.

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:42.640
These are younger, more potent cells.

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:45.920
Again, not keeping them out of the body for as long.

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:52.700
It does really change those markers of both efficacy, but also maybe toxicity as well.

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:58.820
And then this is the late-line data that we have the most follow-up for from China.

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:01.840
And this is their, again, relapsed refractory patients.

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:08.580
So, 93% overall response rate, 89.6% VGPR or better, and their duration of response was

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:09.340
38 months.

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:11.540
So, again, this was mostly patients in China.

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:14.980
We know that in the past, we used to think, oh, they don't have as many options.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:19.240
But now, most of those studies that Gurbaksh talked about, those are actually done in China

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:23.560
because they can make their own cars, and each hospital has their own way of doing 10

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:24.300
trials at a time.

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:28.660
So, I take this data actually very seriously, and it looks really, really exciting.

00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:35.540
And then the U.S., they actually started just a year ago, but Phase 1B2 trial in relapsed

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:36.540
refractory myeloma.

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:43.460
Again, this was 23 patients that was presented at ASTCT, I believe, ASH and ASTCT.

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:45.700
They're hoping to get to 80 patients soon.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:47.560
It was more than three prior lines of therapy.

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:50.160
And, of course, patients could not have prior BCMA therapy.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:53.120
And, again, overall response rate, 96%.

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:56.340
That CR rate or better, 78.3%.

00:02:56.340 --> 00:02:58.780
And days to respond, exact 28 days.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:00.400
So, again, pretty impressive.

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:04.020
And then toxicity or MRD level data that we have.

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:08.620
Again, this is a small number of patients, but 94% for those who are evaluable, and then

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:10.380
100% for those who are older patients.

00:03:10.480 --> 00:03:14.600
So, again, the side effect profile being so well tolerated, not having to worry about

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:17.340
the manufacturing for very long, I think is really, really important.

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:21.020
And then no bridging therapy.

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:23.320
Again, no other car will I say that about.

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:28.000
But this one, I do believe that for the majority of patients, because we get these cells within

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:28.500
two weeks.

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:31.840
It still takes about 28 days on a trial to get this into the patient.

00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:36.040
But, again, we get the cells so quickly that we haven't had to have bridging therapy.

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:38.860
And those patients still do really well without major toxicity.

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:44.640
So, again, no grade four or higher infections, no dose limiting toxicities, and 35% of their

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:46.340
patients were outpatient because of this.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:49.240
So, again, pretty impressive in my opinion.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:51.760
So, again, I think it's a fantastic car.

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:54.500
I think it's different because of the way it's manufactured.

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:55.740
Maybe not the CD19.

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:57.840
But, again, maybe it's a little bit of both.

00:03:58.060 --> 00:03:58.480
But, again...

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:01.540
I really want to hear what everybody else on the panel thinks.
